public class PowerOfThree {
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        // Check for special cases
        if (n < 1 || n > Integer.MAX_VALUE / 3) {
            return false;
        }

        // Use bitwise AND operation to check if the last digit is 1
        while (n % 3 == 0 && n != 1) {
            n /= 3;
        }

        // If n is still divisible by 3 after checking all digits, it means n has more than one '1' bit
        return n == 1;
    }
}
```

This solution works because when we divide a number by 3 repeatedly until it becomes 1 or less than 1, we effectively remove the trailing '1' bits from the binary representation of the number. If at any point during this process, the remainder is not zero, it means the number was not originally a power of three. The final condition checks whether the result is equal to 1, indicating that only one '1' bit remained in the original number.

