Here's a simple C++ program to achieve this task:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <map>

int main() {
    std::ifstream input_file("input.txt"); // Open the input file for reading
    if (!input_file.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Error opening the file." << std::endl;
        return -1;
    }

    std::string target_word = "your_target_word"; // Replace 'your_target_word' with the desired word you want to count
    std::map<std::string, int> word_count;

    std::string line;
    while (getline(input_file, line)) {
        std::istringstream iss(line);
        std::string token;

        while (iss >> token) {
            if (token == target_word) {
                ++word_count[token];
            }
        }
    }

    input_file.close();

    std::cout << "The word '" << target_word << "' appears " << word_count[target_word] << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this code, we first include necessary libraries like `iostream`, `fstream`, `string`, and `map`. Then, we define our target word and create a map to store the word count. The map is initialized with string keys and integer values.

We open the input file using `ifstream` and check whether it was successfully opened. If not, we print an error message and exit the program.

Next, we read each line from the file using `getline` function and split the line into tokens using `istringstream`. We iterate through these tokens and increment the counter for the target word when found.

Finally, after processing all lines, we close the file and display the result on the console.

Make sure to replace `"your_target_word"` with your actual target word before running the program. Also, don't forget to save the above code in a .cpp file and compile it using a C++ compiler.
